04561nam a22007695i 9780231511117DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024032085  a97802315111177 a10.7312/davi138782doi  a(DE-B1597)458777  a(OCoLC)979909842  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0370502bisacsh04a809/.93353  aHL 11012rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50382:1 aDavidson, Jenny, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBreeding :bA Partial History of the Eighteenth Century /cJenny Davidson. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Breeding Before Biology -- tChapter 1. The Rules of Resemblance -- tChapter 2. Bent -- tChapter 3. Cultures of Improvement -- tChapter 4. A Natural History of Inequality -- tChapter 5. Blots on the Landscape -- tChapter 6. Shibboleths -- tNotes -- tBibliography of Works Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Enlightenment commitment to reason naturally gave rise to a belief in the perfectibility of man. Influenced by John Locke and Jean-Jacques Rousseau, many eighteenth-century writers argued that the proper education and upbringing¿breeding¿could make any man a member of the cultural elite. Yet even in this egalitarian environment, the concept of breeding remained tied to theories of blood lineage, caste distinction, and biological difference. Turning to the works of Locke, Rousseau, Swift, Defoe, and other giants of the British Enlightenment, Jenny Davidson revives the debates that raged over the husbandry of human nature and highlights their critical impact on the development of eugenics, the emergence of fears about biological determinism, and the history of the language itself. Combining rich historical research with a keen sense of story, she links explanations for the physical resemblance between parents and children to larger arguments about culture and society and shows how the threads of this compelling conversation reveal the character of a century. A remarkable intellectual history, Breeding not only recasts the fundamental concerns of the Enlightenment but also uncovers the seeds of thought that bloomed into contemporary notions of human perfectibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBiology in literature. 0aBreeding in literature. 0aBreedingzGreat BritainxPhilosophyxHistoryy18th century. 0aEducation and heredityxPhilosophyxHistoryy18th century. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEugenics in literature. 0aEugenicsxHistoryy18th century. 0aHeredity in literature. 0aLiterature and sciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aNature and nurturezGreat BritainxPhilosophyxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/davi1387840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231511117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231511117/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK